UPDATE texts SET `description`="A satirical play about wealth and its effects on individuals and society. It highlights the problems caused by the unequal distribution of wealth among people and how it can corrupt the minds of individuals." WHERE id=77;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A comic play about women's role in society, censorship, and the power of words. It satirizes women's intellectual and moral inferiority, and their obsession with male approval." WHERE id=78;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A comedy about family conflict, politics, and corruption. It mocks the hypocrisy of Athenian politicians and the narrow-mindedness of the older generation, while showcasing the open-mindedness and courage of the younger generation." WHERE id=79;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A drama about sacrifice, love and the triumph of life over death. It tells the story of Alcestis, the wife of Admetus, who sacrifices herself to save his life and the impact of her decision on those around her." WHERE id=80;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about the consequences of war and violence. It tells the story of Andromache, the widow of Hector, and her struggle to protect her son from being killed by her new husband. It also deals with themes of honor, revenge, and the value of human life." WHERE id=81;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragic play about the power of nature, ecstasy, and the dangers of excess. It tells the story of the god Dionysus, who returns to Thebes and seeks revenge on the city for denying his divinity. It also explores themes of gender identity, freedom, and the clash between rationality and instinct." WHERE id=82;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A satyr play that is the only complete surviving example of the genre. It retells the story of the Cyclops from Homer's Odyssey, in which Odysseus and his men are trapped in the cave of the Cyclops, Polyphemus. The play features elements of farce and burlesque, and satirizes Greek stereotypes." WHERE id=83;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about revenge, justice and the complexities of family relationships. It tells the story of Electra and her brother Orestes, who seek revenge against their mother and her lover for the murder of their father. It explores themes of grief, loyalty, and the conflict between individual passions and social norms." WHERE id=84;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about the horrors of war, the consequences of revenge, and the vulnerability of women in times of conflict. It tells the story of Hecuba, the queen of Troy, who becomes a slave after the fall of Troy. The play explores themes of grief, loss of identity, and the ethical implications of taking revenge." WHERE id=85;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A reimagining of the Trojan War and the character of Helen of Troy. It questions the morality of war and the concept of beauty as a justification for violence. The play depicts Helen as an innocent victim of the gods' deception, rather than a willing participant in the conflict." WHERE id=86;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about xenia, the ancient Greek concept of hospitality, and the relationship between individual and community. It tells the story of the children of Heracles, who seek asylum in Athens and are rejected by the king. The play explores themes of loyalty, justice, and the tension between individual desires and social obligations." WHERE id=87;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about the effects of guilt, anger, and mental illness. It tells the story of Heracles, who returns home to find that his wife and children have been killed by his enemies. The play deals with themes of vengeance, justice, and the psychological toll of trauma and revenge." WHERE id=88;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about love, passion, and the destructive power of desire. It depicts the story of the mythological figure Hippolytus, who is killed by his stepmother, Phaedra, after he rejects her advances. The play explores themes of sexual repression, misogyny, and the conflict between reason and the irrational forces of emotion." WHERE id=89;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about family and identity, centered on the story of Ion, the abandoned son of the god Apollo. The play explores themes of motherhood, fate, and the responsibilities of parents towards their children. It raises questions about the purpose of human existence and the role of the gods in shaping human destiny." WHERE id=90;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about sacrifice, war, and the ethics of power. It tells the story of Iphigenia, who is sacrificed by her father, Agamemnon, in order to appease the goddess Artemis and ensure a safe voyage to Troy. The play explores themes of duty, honor, and the conflict between individual lives and societal ideals." WHERE id=91;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about redemption, forgiveness, and the complexities of identity. It tells the story of Iphigenia, who is rescued from her sacrificial fate and taken to Tauris. The play explores themes of family, betrayal, and the quest for self-knowledge." WHERE id=92;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about a woman's revenge against her unfaithful husband, who betrays her for a younger woman. It explores themes of gender roles, passion, and betrayal. It raises questions about justice, morality, and the tragic consequences of unchecked arrogance and ambition." WHERE id=93;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about the aftermath of revenge, the costs of violence, and the power of forgiveness. It tells the story of Orestes, who is haunted by the Furies after he kills his mother and her lover in order to avenge his father's murder. The play explores themes of justice, guilt, and the possibility of redemption." WHERE id=94;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about family, power, and political allegiances. It tells the story of Polyneices and Eteocles, the warring sons of Oedipus. The play explores themes of civil war, loyalty, and the moral obligation to one's community versus one's family." WHERE id=95;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about the consequences of war and the destructive power of pride. It retells the story of the Iliad from the perspective of the Trojans, and depicts the character of Rhesus, a Thracian warrior who fights on the side of the Trojans. The play explores themes of violence, honor, and the futility of war." WHERE id=96;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about refugees, justice, and the ethical obligations of international relations. It tells the story of the daughters of Danaus, who seek asylum in Argos after escaping a forced marriage. The play explores themes of hospitality, morality, and the experiences of those who are marginalized and powerless in times of conflict." WHERE id=97;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about war and its impact on women, children and the powerless. It tells the story of the women of Troy, who are enslaved by the Greeks after the fall of the city. The play explores themes of grief, loss, and the human cost of violence." WHERE id=98;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about honor, reputation, and the psychological toll of warfare. It tells the story of Ajax, a Greek warrior who goes mad after being denied recognition for his heroism in battle. The play explores themes of shame, pride, and the effects of trauma on a soldier's psyche." WHERE id=99;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about civil disobedience, family conflict, and the power of the state. It tells the story of Antigone, who defies the king's order and buries her brother, who was killed during a civil war. The play explores themes of justice, morality, and the tension between the demands of the individual conscience and the needs of society." WHERE id=100;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about revenge, grief, and the complexities of family relationships. It tells the story of Electra, who seeks revenge against her mother and stepfather for murdering her father. The play explores themes of duty, loyalty, and the tension between individual desires and social norms." WHERE id=101;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A play about aging, legacy, and the power of prophecy. It is set in the final days of Oedipus, who is seeking refuge in Colonus. The play explores themes of mortality, dignity and the conflict between individual and societal interests." WHERE id=102;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A tragedy about fate, pride, and the search for personal identity. It tells the story of Oedipus, who unknowingly kills his father and marries his mother, in fulfillment of a prophecy. The play explores themes of conspiracy, destiny, and the limits of free will." WHERE id=103;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="An oration that accuses the Athenian statesman Alcibiades of impiety and sacred crime during his invasion of Sicily. Andocides also claims to have been involved in a previous scandal, known as the Mutilation of the Herms, in which statues of the god Hermes were defaced." WHERE id=243;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="An autobiographical speech in which Andocides pleads with his fellow Athenians to restore his citizenship, which had been revoked after he was accused of involvement in the Mutilation of the Herms. He argues that he is not guilty of the crime and that his service to Athens prior to his exile should be taken into consideration." WHERE id=241;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="An oration in which Andocides defends himself against charges of impiety related to the Eleusinian Mysteries, a religious tradition with secret initiation rites. He explains that he was falsely accused and denounces the informants who accused him as unreliable and untrustworthy." WHERE id=240;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="An oration in favor of peace with Sparta, delivered during the Peloponnesian War. Andocides argues that the Athenians should reconcile with their enemies in order to end the costly and destructive conflict." WHERE id=242;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A speech in which Antiphon accuses a stepmother of poisoning her husband, his own father. He argues that she acted out of greed and jealousy towards his inheritance and demands that she be punished for her crime." WHERE id=244;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A collection of four speeches attributed to Antiphon that deal with the same legal case. The speeches deal with themes of inheritance, murder, and the nature of justice. They demonstrate Antiphon's skill in constructing persuasive rhetorical arguments and his mastery of the technique known as stichomythia." WHERE id=245;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A work that deals with the types of people who were responsible for staging plays in Athens, the choreutes. Antiphon argues that the choreutes should be held accountable for the quality of the performances and the moral messages they convey, and that they should not be allowed to promote their personal interests over the public good." WHERE id=247;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="An oration in which Antiphon accuses a man named Nicomachus of murdering his father, Herodes. He provides evidence and argues for Nicomachus's guilt in a persuasive and organized manner." WHERE id=246;

UPDATE texts SET `description`="A collection of four speeches attributed to Antiphon that deal with various legal cases. The speeches deal with themes of property rights, inheritance, and the nature of evidence. They demonstrate Antiphon's rhetorical skill and his ability to construct logical and persuasive arguments." WHERE id=472;
